Hindi Livinus, Yola The Governor of Adamawa State, Ahmadu Fintiri, has assured the people of the state that the recovery programme initiated by his administration, will soon yield the desired dividend through the reduction of poverty and underdevelopment. Fintiri gave the assurance while speaking during an inspection tour of 15 ongoing roads projects totaling over a 100km, within the state capital, on Saturday. He also apologized to residents and citizens of the state who felt offended by actions taken by his administration to retrieve public and private property looted by hoodlums under the guise of palliatives. Citizens of the state had in a series of social media posts, reacted angrily to the ultimatum given to looters by the governor to return looted items and his threat to demolish any property used as storage facility for the looted items. Speaking during the inspection, Fintiri said, “We have apologised to anyone for whatever mistakes we may have made. Whether knowingly or unknowingly, we just have to move forward as a state. “Both for the rich and the poor we are narrowing the gap, through our free education programme. “Our interventions in various sectors including, health rural roads construction and our urban renewal development projects through the construction of three flyovers, in the state we hope will bring economic recovery and free her citizens from the shackles of poverty and underdevelopment. It is just a matter of time before they begin to see the gains of our recovery mission.” Copyright PUNCH.
